04298nam a22005055i 9780226259796DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226259796  a(DE-B1597)523690  a(OCoLC)912422410  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB2741b.P57 2016 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1932231 aPippin, Robert B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInteranimations :bReceiving Modern German Philosophy /cRobert B. Pippin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Rigorism and the New Kant -- t2. Robert Brandom’s Hegel -- t3. John McDowell’s Germans -- t4. Slavoj Žižek’s Hegel -- t5. Axel Honneth’s Hegelianism -- t6. Alexander Nehamas’s Nietzsche -- t7. Bernard Williams on Nietzsche on the Greeks -- t8. Heidegger on Nietzsche on Nihilism -- t9. Leo Strauss’s Nietzsche -- t10. The Expressivist Nietzsche -- t11. Alasdair MacIntyre’s Modernity -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this latest book, renowned philosopher and scholar Robert B. Pippin offers the thought-provoking argument that the study of historical figures is not only an interpretation and explication of their views, but can be understood as a form of philosophy itself. In doing so, he reconceives philosophical scholarship as a kind of network of philosophical interanimations, one in which major positions in the history of philosophy, when they are themselves properly understood within their own historical context, form philosophy’s lingua franca. Examining a number of philosophers to explore the nature of this interanimation, he presents an illuminating assortment of especially thoughtful examples of historical commentary that powerfully enact philosophy. After opening up his territory with an initial discussion of contemporary revisionist readings of Kant’s moral theory, Pippin sets his sights on his main objects of interest: Hegel and Nietzsche. Through them, however, he offers what few others could: an astonishing synthesis of an immense and diverse set of thinkers and traditions. Deploying an almost dialogical, conversational approach, he pursues patterns of thought that both shape and, importantly, connect the major traditions: neo-Aristotelian, analytic, continental, and postmodern, bringing the likes of Heidegger, Honneth, MacIntyre, McDowell, Brandom, Strauss, Williams, and Žižek—not to mention Hegel and Nietzsche— into the same philosophical conversation. By means of these case studies, Pippin mounts an impressive argument about a relatively under discussed issue in professional philosophy—the bearing of work in the history of philosophy on philosophy itself—and thereby he argues for the controversial thesis that no strict separation between the domains is defensible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPhilosophy, Germany19th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022625965940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226259796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226259796/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles